<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1909-01-22T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1909-01-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="52" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d52">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 836/123.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Brazilian Ambassador</gloss>
                                to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Brazilian Embassy</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1909-01-22"><hi rend="italic">January 22,
                                1909</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary of State</hi>: I have the honor to
                            bring to your knowledge that, according to a communication just received
                            from the Brazilian Government, by a decree No. 7283, of the 14th of
                            January instant, the ministry of finance renewed for the present fiscal
                            year the reduction of 20 per cent previously granted to the American
                            flour and to other articles imported in Brazil from the United States of
                            America.</p>
                        <p>I avail, etc,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Joaquim Nabuco.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>